      <h4><small>RECENT POSTS</small></h4>
      <hr>
      <h2>Lesson 1</h2>
      <h5><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-time"></span> Post by Graham, Jun 30, 2020.</h5>
      <h5><span class="label label-danger">Jupyter</span> <span class="label label-primary">Python</span></h5><br>
      <p>
	Welcome to the first lesson of CS101! These posts will serve as short summaries of Zoom lectures for those that were unable to attend, or for those who would like an abbreviated version of the material covered. We'll start by setting up our environment, and end with a few simple problems to familiarize ourselves with editing and running a file. The editor we will use for writing our code is <a href="https://jupyter.org/">Jupyter Notebook</a>.
      </p>
      <br><br>
      
      <h4><small>OLDER</small></h4>
      <hr>
      <h2>Welcome!</h2>
      <h5><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-time"></span> Post by Graham, Jun 30, 2020.</h5>
      <h5><span class="label label-success">Admin</span></h5><br>
      <p>
	Welcome to CS101's Summer Bootcamp for 2020! This class is meant to provide you with an introduction to basic programming. Students will become familiar with the necessary skills to create programs and projects by themselves. We'll use Python for this class, arguably the most popular programming language in the world right now, for its easy learning curve and powerfu capabilities in various computing fields. Some of the things you will learn in this class include fundamentals such as:
<ul>
  <li>Creating scripts with Python</li>
  <li>Running, saving, and deploying your work using Jupyter Notebook</li>
  <li>Solving problems found on real coding interviews</li>
  <li>Basic number theory and math concepts to strengthen your coding ability</li>
</ul>
My goal is to provide beginners with all of the tools necessary to begin exploring programming on their own. Through simple exercises and problem-solving acitivities, students will develop skills on their own; my role is to help demystify coding so that anyone can get the hang of writing their own programs. 
      </p>
